One-liner: The most sub par Dim Sum experience I have had in my life.  Bullet points: 1. Chicken feet was great 8/10 2. Turnip cake was good 7/10 3. Yangzhou fried rice was ok, under seasoned and the roasted meat was tasteless and dry. 6/10 4. Shrimp dumpling was ok. The shrimp was given generously but the dumpling as a whole was tasteless.5/10 5. Shrimp Shumai was similar to the dumplings. 5/10 6. 金菇牛腸粉 (I think that is what it's called). Terrible. The dish was served lukewarm, and does not have much taste in it. The meat in it had a starchy texture without any taste. It was almost like eating tasteless apple sauce while I was expecting the flavor of beef. 0/10 7. XLB was the biggest disappointment of the night. Coming from Taiwan, I was expecting XLB that is fresh in firm but thin dough wrapping up delicious broth and fresh ground pork with scallions. The XLB here came in little tin cups that looked like it came out of a box from the store. The meat inside the XLB was tasteless, starchy, and pink. I have eaten way too many XLB in my life to think that it is normal to have an XLB like that. When I asked the wait staff, I was told that is how they get the XLB to have broth inside. They then told me that it is different from ones in China or Taiwan and it is delicious that way. I have never had such a disappointing XLB experience. 0/10 8. Wait staff attitude and service was unprofessional. The wait staff did not introduce how the ordering was done, even though at the time there were about 5 other tables in this big restaurant. I had to ask for soy sauce 3 times before the actual soy sauce was delivered to me. The first time they gave me chili oil, the second time they gave me sweet soy paste (some call it thick soy sauce but ti delivers a drastically different flavor than soy sauce), and the third time they brought a bottle of Kikoman soy sauce without any dipping container so I had to ask for that an extra time.  My roommate and I ended up paying $55 for the meal (about 17.5% tip) but we are less than thrilled about our entire dining experience there. I personally will not go back to this restaurant again.

They don't have the best ambience or service, but it doesn't matter, because the food is AWESOME and the price is right!  We came on a Monday afternoon and it was not crowded and service was fast. We ordered and had Dim Sum only.  Food: 5/5 - All of the Dim Sum we ate were really great! The porridge, SiuMai, and BBQ pork pastry were the standouts! Each of these three dishes were well made, huge and delicious! The Pork pastry was much larger than I anticipated and the filling are generous too, though the edges had a bit too much flour. Another standout here is the BEEF TENDONS! This is not found elsewhere and it is one of our family's favorite dishes!  Presentation: 3/5. Food is not as polished but as long as they taste good I don't mind. Ambience: 3/5. This is a typical Asian restaurant experience, dark and a little aged, but clean nonetheless. Price: 5/5! Very competitively priced but does not sacrifice quality  Conclusion, this will be our go to place to have Dim Sum in the future! Sure, MingHin is still the king of DimSum and has a better restaurant ambience and service. But Cai is not far off and lighter on the wallet!

I really enjoyed watching the celebration - a bit of a candid cultural exhibition.  We took advantage of the all day dim sum, and the food was very good. I usually go to the same Chinese restaurants, but I'm so happy I stop by Cai tonight. It's in the new China Town, right by Cermak Red Line stop. It's on the second floor and is very spacious. Very friendly waitresses. They didn't mind when I kept asking for more hot chilli oil sauce. They also serve dim sum all day. We ordered shrimp egg rolls, orange beef, beef fried rice, and salt n pepper squid. Everything was so fresh. Fried rice was very good and not greasy at all. I will definitely come back! The tables next to us order ducks and shrimps and they look amazing. The restaurant is known for fresh seafood as well. Cai made it to my new favorite Chinese restaurant.

I can't actually review their food because as soon as my husband went to enter their restaurant at 10:15p.m. (website says they close at 11p.m., hours posted on the door say Midnight), a restaurant employee rushed to block the unlocked door and told us that they were closed.  I asked her what were their hours, and she said they close at 11:00.  I pointed to her that it was only 10:15.  She gave me an awkward look and said they weren't taking anymore orders.  We are from out of town and, after seeing favorable reviews, went thru ALOT of trouble there, including a $6 Uber ride and wandering around for 20 minutes trying to find the 2nd floor location.  By the time we arrived, we were super hungry and in unfamiliar territory. Being turned away so suddenly was disappointing and frustrating. When dining while Black, one can't help but question such impromptu restaurant closures.

Service was hardly a primary concern in this Chinese restaurant, though, the Dim Sum that it has was probably the best of all Chicago area. I was quite surprised with the quality of food here, which I felt fresh, not-from-frozen-package, flavorful, and succulent. Similar to most of the Dim Sum restaurants in Chinatown, the food was ordered off a menu. What I like about the service here was that they did not bring the food altogether at once. The food was served one by one so that we always had it hot and steamy. The table was clear quickly spending room for the new dish. Highly recommend: Baked Green Chived Puffs (super crispy w/ sweet and sour sauce), Xiao Long Bao (juicy and luscious), Shrimp Dumpling w/ Green Chive (succulent), Steamed Creamy Egg Yolk Bun (made from salted egg yolk, creamy, smooth, and rich). One off-menu but the highly recommended item, which was traditional Chinese's smooth, dulcet, sweet treat that we found: Douhua (soybean pudding alike, made with very soft tofu, dipped in sugar ginger syrup). What I liked but did not surprise me: Celery w/ Shrimp Rice Noodle, BBQ Pork Rice Noodle, Pan Fried Pot Stickers, Seafood and Spinach Dumpling, Siu Mai, Sticky Rice Cake. What I did not like: Vegetarian Duck (I would instead order the real duck over this), Steamed Chicken Feet w/ Peking Sauce, Shredded Duck Crystal Dumpling (looked good but did not taste good), Chiu Chow Dumpling w/ Mince Pork and Peanuts, Pan Fried Turnip Cake. The price was pretty higher than other places of the same category. All in all, this place is my new favorite Dim Sum restaurant that I could spend my Saturday morning with.

I can't begin to elaborate how awful this place is. Firstly, their food is so inconsistent. After giving this place so many chances, there has never, ever, been a redeeming factor. This restaurant is very popular for Chinese weddings, so majority of the time that I'm there, it's for that sole reason. If I had the choice to not go, I would rather not. Secondly, Cai is probably one of, if not, the most expensive Dim Sum places in Chinatown. For such prices, you would assume better service, which isn't the case. Thirdly, their layout/floor-plan, lacks any consideration for people to get up and move. Tables are squished so tightly together, everyone might as well be sitting at one large communal table. Overall, I honestly do not recommend coming to this place unless you have a very close friend or relative, whose wedding you must attend, at which point, you have my sincerest condolences.
